Page 1: Virtual Memory Fundamentals
Virtual Memory & Paging
The Problem: Limited RAM. Every program needs memory (RAM) to run, including space for instructions, stack, variables, and the heap
.
Example: If you have 8GB RAM but your programs (Chrome, VS Code, and Games) require a total of 11GB, the RAM is insufficient
.
Definition: Virtual memory is a technique used by the operating system to use disk space as an extension of RAM
.
Core Idea: It is a memory management technique that allows programs to use more memory than is physically available by temporarily storing inactive memory pages on disk
.
Simplified Formula: RAM + DISK = Virtual Memory
.
Disk Role: The disk acts like extra memory
.
Swap Space: The specific disk area used as extra memory is known as Swap space
.
System Capacity Example: 8GB RAM + 6GB Disk Space = 14GB Total System Memory
.

