Page 2: Demand Paging & Address Space
Key Idea of Virtual Memory:
The OS does not load the entire program into RAM; instead, it loads only the parts currently needed (e.g., specific code, stack, or data segments)
.
For example, if only 10% of a program is used at a time, only that 10% is loaded into RAM while the rest remains on the disk
.
Demand Paging:
Virtual memory uses a technique called Demand Paging
.
A page of memory is loaded only when the program needs it
.
Example: If a program needs a calculate_tax() function, the OS loads only the memory containing that function; other functions stay on the disk
.
Virtual Address Space:
Each program "thinks" it has its own large, private memory space (e.g., 4GB)
.
In reality, physical RAM (e.g., 8GB) is shared between many processes
.

