Page 3: Paging vs. Contiguous Allocation
Virtual Address vs. Physical Memory:
This creates an illusion of a virtual address space
.
A program uses a Virtual Address (e.g., 0x2340), which the system maps to a Physical Address (the actual location in RAM hardware)
.
Key Points:
Programs larger than the physical RAM can run
.
Multiple programs can run simultaneously
.
Ensures process isolation
.
Provides efficient memory usage, as active memory stays in RAM
.
Paging:
Before paging, the OS used contiguous memory allocation, where a process had to be stored in one continuous block of RAM
.
Problem: This often led to fragmentation, where there was enough total free memory but not enough continuous memory to fit a new process
.
Page Fault Intro:
If the CPU requests memory that is not currently in RAM, a page fault occurs
.
Steps to resolve: Pause process → Load page from disk → Update mapping → Resume process
.

